# Chapter 9 — Strings ensemble

Chapter 3 introduced the strings — violin, viola, cello, double bass. This chapter is about how they play together: the quartet, the section, the ensemble voice.

Four strings playing together sound like one bigger string. That's the trick of ensemble — voices that would otherwise be four become a single, richer thing.

## The quartet

The classical string quartet: two violins, viola, cello.

```scheme
(define string-quartet
  '((violin-1  first-voice   high-melody)
    (violin-2  second-voice  counter-line)
    (viola     middle-voice  warm-harmony)
    (cello     bass-voice    low-anchor)))

(for-each (lambda (p) (display p) (newline)) string-quartet)
```

Output:

```
(violin-1 first-voice high-melody)
(violin-2 second-voice counter-line)
(viola middle-voice warm-harmony)
(cello bass-voice low-anchor)
```

Four voices covering four registers.

## Divisi and unison

Strings can either play together or split into parts.

```scheme
(define (make-passage mode voices) (list 'passage mode voices))

(display (make-passage 'unison '(all-play-the-melody)))       (newline)
(display (make-passage 'divisi '((half play-A) (half play-C)))) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(passage unison (all-play-the-melody))
(passage divisi ((half play-A) (half play-C)))
```

Unison gets warmth from doubling. Divisi builds harmony from within the section.

## Pizzicato vs arco

Two fundamental ways to make the string sound: bow (arco) or pluck (pizzicato).

```scheme
(define (playing-style style)
  (case style
    ((arco)       '(bowed-sustained-warm))
    ((pizzicato)  '(plucked-short-percussive))
    ((col-legno)  '(bow-wood-on-string-clacky))
    ((sul-pont)   '(bow-near-bridge-glassy))
    ((sul-tasto)  '(bow-over-fingerboard-hollow))))

(display (playing-style 'arco))       (newline)
(display (playing-style 'pizzicato))  (newline)
(display (playing-style 'col-legno))  (newline)
```

Output:

```
(bowed-sustained-warm)
(plucked-short-percussive)
(bow-wood-on-string-clacky)
```

Five styles, five completely different textures. The same instrument becomes five things.

## The full string section

An orchestra's string section is many more voices.

```scheme
(define (string-section)
  '((first-violins   16 lead-melody)
    (second-violins  14 harmony-counter)
    (violas          12 middle-warm)
    (cellos          10 bass-melody)
    (double-basses    8 low-anchor)))

(for-each (lambda (p) (display p) (newline)) (string-section))
```

Output:

```
(first-violins 16 lead-melody)
(second-violins 14 harmony-counter)
(violas 12 middle-warm)
(cellos 10 bass-melody)
(double-basses 8 low-anchor)
```

60 players, five sections. The pyramid narrows toward the bass.

## Balance

The number of players per section balances the natural volume of the instrument.

```scheme
(define (why-more-violins?)
  '(violins-project-less-than-basses
    so-more-violins-are-needed-to-balance))

(display (why-more-violins?)) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(violins-project-less-than-basses so-more-violins-are-needed-to-balance)
```

Sixteen violins balance eight basses. That's ensemble math.

## A chamber piece

Small ensembles are quartets, quintets, sextets.

```scheme
(define (make-ensemble name players) (list 'ensemble name 'players players))

(display (make-ensemble 'quartet 4)) (newline)
(display (make-ensemble 'quintet 5)) (newline)
(display (make-ensemble 'sextet  6)) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(ensemble quartet players 4)
(ensemble quintet players 5)
(ensemble sextet players 6)
```

## What you know now

- The string quartet is the atom of chamber music.
- Divisi splits one section into voices; unison doubles.
- Arco, pizzicato, col legno, sul ponticello, sul tasto — five distinct textures.
- Section sizes balance instrument projection: 16 violins to 8 basses.

## Try before you turn the page

```scheme
(display (list 'a 'quartet 'is 'four 'voices 'that 'sound 'like 'one 'bigger 'string)) (newline)
```

If you can shape a string ensemble, you're ready for the full roster.

